The Completed gweb4.sh Script

This version contains all the required substitutions, including the HTML escaping (sed), string splitting (cut), and the specific absolute directory paths required by Einstein.
Bash

#!/bin/bash

# 1. Change to the Einstein testing directory
cd /shared/humphrys/shakespeare 

# 2. Define the function to make the output clickable
clickable()
{
 while read line
 do
  # Extract everything BEFORE the first colon (the filename)
  file=`echo "$line" | cut -d ':' -f 1`
  
  # Extract everything AFTER the first colon (the actual text hit)
  # -f 2- means field 2 and everything after it, in case the text itself contains a colon
  hit=`echo "$line" | cut -d ':' -f 2-`
 
  # Apply the absolute Einstein prefix so the links work from $HOME/gweb.html
  echo "<a href='/shared/humphrys/shakespeare/$file'>$file</a>: $hit <br>"
 done
}

# 3. Redirect all subsequent script output to the target file
exec > "$HOME/gweb.html"

# 4. Output the HTML preformatted tag
echo "<pre>"

# 5. Search, escape HTML brackets so they print literally, and pipe to the clickable function
# The sed command replaces < with &lt; and > with &gt;
grep -i "$1" */*html | sed -e 's/</\&lt;/g' -e 's/>/\&gt;/g' | clickable

# 6. Close the preformatted tag
echo "</pre>"

How the Missing Parts Work

    [sed command]: sed -e 's/</\&lt;/g' -e 's/>/\&gt;/g'
    Because the text being searched is raw HTML, it contains tags like <b> or <i>. If you output these directly into your gweb.html file, the browser will try to render them, making a mess of the page. This sed command converts the brackets into HTML entities (&lt; and &gt;), forcing the browser to display them as literal text.

    [cut before the colon]: cut -d ':' -f 1
    The -d ':' tells cut to use the colon as the delimiter (the separator between fields). -f 1 grabs the very first field, which grep uses for the filename.

    [cut after the colon]: cut -d ':' -f 2-
    The -f 2- tells cut to grab the second field and everything after it. This prevents the text from being cut off early if a character in the Shakespeare play happens to use a colon in their dialogue.

    [some other prefix]: /shared/humphrys/shakespeare/
    Because your script writes the output web page to $HOME, a relative link like <a href='macbeth/complete.html'> would make the browser look inside $HOME/macbeth/. By hardcoding the absolute path /shared/humphrys/shakespeare/ in front of the filename, the browser knows exactly where to find the target files on the Einstein server.
